# A quote closing over a generic def input applied to an overloaded
# builtin infers as an overloaded thunk — here `(@x toFloat)` is
# ( -- Maybe[float]) | ( -- float). Using it as an iff branch must pick
# the arm that agrees with the sibling branch and the declared output
# (the float arm), not greedily commit to the first arm.
def pick (a -- float)
  x!
  true (@x toFloat) (1.5) iff
end
3 pick str wl
